00:22:49,811 --> 00:22:51,750
Speaker 0: That's just because you use a giant freak towel.

295
00:22:52,110 --> 00:22:53,070
Speaker 1: A giant awesome towel.

296
00:22:54,270 --> 00:22:54,869
Speaker 1: Bring your own towel.

297
00:22:55,530 --> 00:22:59,710
Speaker 0: Yeah, bring your own towel, and if you have extra people, bring your own pillows, blankets, all the extras.

298
00:23:00,832 --> 00:23:03,590
Speaker 0: All the stuff that you might need that you would otherwise ask for the hotel.

299
00:23:04,250 --> 00:23:06,070
Speaker 1: The awesome people get dibs on beds.

300
00:23:06,470 --> 00:23:13,690
Speaker 0: Generally, that's the one perk, because we've been talking about how difficult it is, and time consuming, and frustrating to actually manage this for all your friends.

301
00:23:14,311 --> 00:23:19,525
Speaker 0: The main perk is that if you do all this, you're pretty much guaranteed a bed, because you did it.

302
00:23:19,545 --> 00:23:21,590
Speaker 0: You can just kick people out of your room if they don't comply.

303
00:23:22,090 --> 00:23:22,170
Speaker 0: Yup.

304
00:23:23,810 --> 00:23:28,870
Speaker 0: Now, rule number two, do not ever request anything extra from the hotel.

305
00:23:29,330 --> 00:23:33,330
Speaker 1: You don't want room service, you don't even want the rollaway bed, you want nothing.

306
00:23:33,530 --> 00:23:35,430
Speaker 0: Yeah, especially never ask for the rollaway bed.

307
00:23:35,510 --> 00:23:37,049
Speaker 1: They often charge for the rollaway bed.

308
00:23:37,170 --> 00:23:44,050
Speaker 0: Yes, and if you ask for the rollaway bed, they'll come into your room and they might see, you know, ten sets of bags where there should only be four.

309
00:23:44,830 --> 00:23:49,630
Speaker 1: The other thing is, normally when you go on vacation, your hotel room is full of, like, your clothes and your toiletries.

310
00:23:49,830 --> 00:23:55,550
Speaker 1: So you can let room service, you know, not room service, that's ordering food, uh, housekeeping, come in and clean up all you want.

311
00:23:55,950 --> 00:24:06,330
Speaker 1: But at a con, your room is full of, like, drinks, snacks, toys, con goodies, extra people, con badges, all kinds of crazy shit.

312
00:24:06,712 --> 00:24:10,790
Speaker 1: And it's just a mess everywhere, and you really don't want housekeeping touching anything.

313
00:24:11,150 --> 00:24:19,830
Speaker 0: So that's rule number three, do not ever request housekeeping, and make sure you put the Do Not Disturb thing on your doorknob 24/7.

314
00:24:19,830 --> 00:24:21,309
Speaker 1: Yup, never let it get off there.

315
00:24:21,890 --> 00:24:26,650
Speaker 1: And if there isn't a Do Not Disturb thingy in your room, go ask for one at the desk.

316
00:24:27,073 --> 00:24:28,029
Speaker 0: Or make one.

317
00:24:28,410 --> 00:24:31,119
Speaker 1: Yeah, don't call them up and say, "Bring me one,".

318
00:24:31,199 --> 00:24:33,547
Speaker 1: go down to the desk and say, "Can I have a Do Not Disturb

319
00:24:33,587 --> 00:24:33,788
Speaker 1: sign?".

320
00:24:34,732 --> 00:24:36,129
Speaker 1: That way, they don't come in your room and look.

321
00:24:36,930 --> 00:24:37,070
Speaker 0: Yup.

322
00:24:37,692 --> 00:24:43,430
Speaker 0: Now, rule number three is don't have everyone go up to the desk when you check in.

323
00:24:43,950 --> 00:24:52,150
Speaker 0: If you walk up to a desk with nine people, and you say, "Checking into room for Decoster, Occupancy 2," they're gonna know.

324
00:24:53,051 --> 00:25:01,370
Speaker 0: Have one guy go check in, and then meet everyone at the room, or go up to the room in stages, or something, you're smart, figure it out.

325
00:25:02,111 --> 00:25:08,230
Speaker 1: Generally, it doesn't matter unless you travel in a big group, because people show up at all kinds of different times.

326
00:25:08,750 --> 00:25:10,981
Speaker 1: So those people just show up and be like, "Hey, what room are you

327
00:25:11,021 --> 00:25:11,101
Speaker 1: in?".

328
00:25:11,122 --> 00:25:12,830
Speaker 1: And they go in the elevator and no one knows.

329
00:25:13,090 --> 00:25:15,790
Speaker 1: And maybe one person shows up at a time, maybe two at a time.

330
00:25:16,190 --> 00:25:19,309
Speaker 1: But if you show up at ten people at a time, you have to buffer it.

331
00:25:20,010 --> 00:25:24,190
Speaker 1: You know, stay in the parking garage and then go up into the elevators.

332
00:25:24,950 --> 00:25:29,290
Speaker 1: Or just send one person up to get the keys, then have that person come down and get everyone else.

333
00:25:29,812 --> 00:25:30,996
Speaker 0: Yep, now getting the keys.

334
00:25:31,658 --> 00:25:34,910
Speaker 0: Don't ask for more keys than the room's occupancy.

335
00:25:35,550 --> 00:25:40,890
Speaker 0: So if you have a room with an occupancy of four, you can safely ask for three extra keys, but don't ask for eight.

336
00:25:41,954 --> 00:25:43,230
Speaker 0: It's kind of obvious why you should--.

337
00:25:43,270 --> 00:25:45,610
Speaker 1: Usually the hotels will give you two keys by default.

338
00:25:45,752 --> 00:25:45,925
Speaker 1: Yeah.

339
00:25:46,810 --> 00:25:48,109
Speaker 1: And two might be all you need.

340
00:25:49,250 --> 00:25:52,390
Speaker 0: It's always good to have extras, but you gotta make sure you keep track of them.

341
00:25:52,951 --> 00:25:53,873
Speaker 1: Oh, I forgot.

342
00:25:53,913 --> 00:26:01,670
Speaker 1: We're assuming that you're getting normal rooms with two double beds, which is two queen-sized beds, which is for four people.

343
00:26:01,950 --> 00:26:02,091
Speaker 0: Yes.

344
00:26:02,211 --> 00:26:09,310
Speaker 0: In fact, you should probably request that, because usually it's interchangeable between two double beds or two queen-- Usually it's two queen beds or one king bed.

345
00:26:09,519 --> 00:26:09,710
Speaker 0: Yeah.

346
00:26:09,810 --> 00:26:10,308
Speaker 0: Are your choices.

347
00:26:11,130 --> 00:26:17,150
Speaker 1: You want two queen bedrooms, and you want as many adjacent rooms as you're gonna need.

348
00:26:17,511 --> 00:26:29,130
Speaker 0: Yeah, most people only get one room, but if you're like us and you start making awesome and all your friends start wanting to stay with you, we get two, three rooms, and with the early check-in, we're assured that we'll get three rooms in a row.

349
00:26:30,110 --> 00:26:31,757
Speaker 0: Because, basically, think of it this way.

350
00:26:32,098 --> 00:26:34,930
Speaker 0: Shower space is pretty much the only reason for this, and also keys.

351
00:26:35,790 --> 00:26:41,250
Speaker 0: If you have eight people in one room, that's eight people who share one bathroom and one shower and four keys.

352
00:26:42,291 --> 00:26:50,550
Speaker 0: If you have sixteen people in two rooms, and the rooms are adjacent, now you have two bathrooms that can be used simultaneously between the two rooms.

353
00:26:50,650 --> 00:26:57,687
Speaker 1: Because you leave the doors that connect the rooms together open at all times, so any key to one room is a key to both of the rooms.

354
00:26:58,529 --> 00:26:58,790
Speaker 1: You see?

355
00:26:59,190 --> 00:27:03,521
Speaker 0: So if you ever go in a big group, unless you're going for a suite or something, just get rooms that are adjacent.

356
00:27:03,541 --> 00:27:06,990
Speaker 0: You'll save money, and it'll make your overstuffing experience a lot better.

357
00:27:07,130 --> 00:27:08,955
Speaker 1: Yeah, a suite is something completely different.

358
00:27:09,035 --> 00:27:11,763
Speaker 1: I can only recommend you get a suite if you're going to have a party.

359
00:27:12,906 --> 00:27:14,610
