00:39:43,934 --> 00:39:46,038
Speaker 0: Just lie straight up, and then you'll never see them again.

542
00:39:46,078 --> 00:39:47,521
Speaker 0: The con's so big, it won't matter.

543
00:39:47,621 --> 00:39:51,810
Speaker 0: Or the con's so small, you're screwed, because they'll follow you around for the whole con.

544
00:39:53,510 --> 00:39:56,614
Speaker 1: Another good idea is to team up with someone who can brush them off.

545
00:39:57,235 --> 00:40:08,750
Speaker 1: You know, a lot of times, if, you know, there'll be a nerdy guy who's trying to bother you, but you're hanging out with someone who he, like, is kind of afraid of going near, even though he really wants to get close to you.

546
00:40:09,191 --> 00:40:14,210
Speaker 1: But as long as you stay close to that safety person, it's sort of like a repelling magnet, you can keep them away.

547
00:40:14,750 --> 00:40:19,730
Speaker 0: Now, at the same time, don't push people away automatically, because you'll meet a lot of cool people, like we said.

548
00:40:19,810 --> 00:40:24,630
Speaker 1: Oh yeah, only brush someone away if they're, like, a super annoying fan person that's just painful to stand next to.

549
00:40:24,690 --> 00:40:29,010
Speaker 0: Yeah, like if a big ol' fat guy comes over and starts telling you about his hentai collection, brush him off.

550
00:40:29,390 --> 00:40:36,029
Speaker 1: Or if a little nerdy kid comes up and says, "Oh my god, DDR, blah blah blah, I can get this on this song, I can get this on this song, oh my god, I beat this song on this song...".

551
00:40:37,035 --> 00:40:38,305
Speaker 1: You say, "Alright, shut up and go

552
00:40:38,346 --> 00:40:38,487
Speaker 1: away.".

553
00:40:39,010 --> 00:40:44,450
Speaker 0: But if you run into, say, us, if you say, "Hey," we'll say, "Hey," and we'll probably end up going to the AMV contest together.

554
00:40:44,650 --> 00:40:46,230
Speaker 1: Yeah, if you say Leroy, we say Jenkins.

555
00:40:49,250 --> 00:40:55,810
Speaker 0: Actually, we went to Otacon, and just so you know, we yelled Leroy, and in fact, an entire crowd of people screamed Jenkins back.

556
00:40:56,610 --> 00:41:02,250
Speaker 1: Yeah, there are certain things you can do with cons, sort of like a litmus test, to tell if people are cool.

557
00:41:02,752 --> 00:41:07,610
Speaker 1: You know, and that's sort of like a really weak one, is to say Leroy and see if they say Jenkins.

558
00:41:07,930 --> 00:41:12,930
Speaker 1: Because if they say Jenkins, that means that, you know, they're cool, happening-on-the-internet type of people.

559
00:41:13,634 --> 00:41:14,170
Speaker 1: You know that much.

560
00:41:14,170 --> 00:41:16,049
Speaker 0: I mean, it depends on what kind of con it is and who you're looking for.

561
00:41:16,570 --> 00:41:16,692
Speaker 0: Mm-hmm.

562
00:41:17,770 --> 00:41:23,423
Speaker 1: Well, if it's, like, BotCon, you can say, like, what's that thing the Transformers say?

563
00:41:23,443 --> 00:41:25,949
Speaker 1: The little internet, the universal...

564
00:41:26,555 --> 00:41:27,170
Speaker 0: I don't even remember.

565
00:41:28,091 --> 00:41:34,370
Speaker 0: Yeah, you know what, because I've seen that movie so many times, but that universal peace thing is so complicated, I've never memorized it.

566
00:41:34,430 --> 00:41:35,770
Speaker 1: It's like Chub Niffy something.

567
00:41:35,992 --> 00:41:36,078
Speaker 1: Yeah.

568
00:41:36,291 --> 00:41:36,950
Speaker 1: I don't even remember.

569
00:41:37,310 --> 00:41:37,827
Speaker 0: Neither do I.

570
00:41:38,350 --> 00:41:39,875
Speaker 1: If I see it, I'll go, "Oh, that's what that...".

571
00:41:39,975 --> 00:41:44,750
Speaker 1: I recognize it immediately, but yeah, if you say that kind of thing, you know, it all depends on the con.

572
00:41:45,150 --> 00:42:08,190
Speaker 0: I mean, the main thing to remember is that while anime cons and gaming cons and all these different geeky cons are all, like, a different subset of geekery... We're kind of leaving out the trade conventions a little bit here, but they're all geeks, and a lot of geeks have similar interests, and they may not be super in... Like, you're in an anime con, there's a good chance you'll find some Linux geeks or some gaming geeks and hang out with them independent of the anime.

573
00:42:09,190 --> 00:42:13,650
Speaker 1: Yeah, you know, I actually didn't watch, really, any anime at all at Otacon.

574
00:42:14,231 --> 00:42:19,070
Speaker 1: I did so few anime-related activities, actually, other than buying anime merchandise, it was scary.

575
00:42:19,331 --> 00:42:25,090
Speaker 0: Yeah, I mean, one of the highlights was seeing Entertainment System, the band, play NES songs for us in a little concert.

576
00:42:26,174 --> 00:42:27,449
Speaker 1: That was one of the things we committed to.

577
00:42:28,031 --> 00:42:29,183
Speaker 0: Yeah, and you know what?

578
00:42:29,204 --> 00:42:29,648
Speaker 0: It was worth it.

579
00:42:30,371 --> 00:42:30,889
Speaker 1: Definitely worth it.

580
00:42:31,250 --> 00:42:36,350
Speaker 1: So, eating at the con is sort of tricky, depending on where the con is at.

581
00:42:36,450 --> 00:42:39,970
Speaker 0: Now, if it's a small con, it really doesn't matter, you don't have to worry about it at all.

582
00:42:40,030 --> 00:42:48,450
Speaker 0: Because every small con I've gone to, basically, everyone just gets together, and then they either go out, because there's a million restaurants nearby, or they order a pizza and have it delivered to the hotel.

583
00:42:49,352 --> 00:42:55,850
Speaker 0: I mean, at UberCon, there were literally like a hundred pizzas delivered to the hotel under various names over the course of the evening on Saturday.

584
00:42:56,432 --> 00:42:59,450
Speaker 1: You never want to eat in the hotel or convention center, ever.

585
00:42:59,690 --> 00:43:01,209
Speaker 0: Yes, that goes doubly so.

586
00:43:01,270 --> 00:43:03,970
Speaker 1: Unless it's free food provided by the convention itself.

587
00:43:04,350 --> 00:43:06,590
Speaker 0: Yeah, Anime Central used to have the most awesome thing.

588
00:43:06,770 --> 00:43:12,309
Speaker 0: I don't know if they still do it, but basically, they had a green room that had infinite free food.

589
00:43:12,851 --> 00:43:20,330
Speaker 0: And by infinite free food, I mean actual food, like sandwiches with meat and cheese on them, and chips and crackers and soda and fruit and drinks.

590
00:43:21,811 --> 00:43:23,610
Speaker 0: It was absolutely free to anyone who went to the con.

591
00:43:24,030 --> 00:43:27,170
Speaker 0: You could go to Anime Central and not spend a dime on food and not die.

592
00:43:27,990 --> 00:43:31,170
Speaker 1: Also, most cons provide free water, so never buy bottled water, ever.

593
00:43:31,410 --> 00:43:33,689
Speaker 0: Yeah, but make sure you have money for food.

594
00:43:34,330 --> 00:43:39,590
Speaker 0: Make sure your group either has a way to get in touch, or has a planned time to meet for dinner.

595
00:43:40,133 --> 00:43:43,070
Speaker 0: Don't worry so much about lunch, because you're all going to be doing different things anyway.

596
00:43:44,293 --> 00:43:47,170
Speaker 0: It takes a long time to organize a group to go out for dinner.

597
00:43:47,650 --> 00:43:53,008
Speaker 1: I usually just take as many people as I can get right now, and then we go, "Okay, good, let's

598
00:43:53,028 --> 00:43:53,129
Speaker 1: eat."

599
00:43:54,695 --> 00:43:57,827
Speaker 1: Our total group of people that we knew at the con was like 30 or 40 people.

600
00:43:59,531 --> 00:44:10,490
Speaker 0: And we always organize the crazy dinners, because it takes about an hour to gather a group of that size, get them together, get them all to agree on a restaurant, drag them all there, sit them all down, and then finally start eating.

601
00:44:11,031 --> 00:44:12,709
Speaker 0: You don't want to do that three times a day.

602
00:44:13,630 --> 00:44:18,150
Speaker 0: So over lunch, me and Scott and five or six other people would all find each other and go eat.

603
00:44:18,750 --> 00:44:22,746
Speaker 0: And then while we're eating, we'd see half of our group come in to eat, just as we're leaving.

604
00:44:22,826 --> 00:44:23,670
Speaker 0: We kind of trade off.

605
00:44:26,432 --> 00:44:31,170
Speaker 1: And the other thing is, you have to know the food places in the area.

606
00:44:31,330 --> 00:44:38,290
Speaker 1: I remember the first Otacon, I didn't really realize that the walkway went to the little mini mall with the food court.

607
00:44:38,490 --> 00:44:42,450
Speaker 0: Yep, I walked across the street to this other crat mall, and all they had was pizza, and it was bad pizza.

608
00:44:43,070 --> 00:44:51,970
Speaker 1: Yeah, so make sure before you eat to ask either people at the con or con staff or someone where the food is at.

609
00:44:52,610 --> 00:44:58,989
Speaker 0: If it's a hotel or you're in a hotel, the concierge will always know good restaurants, and they're usually very polite about it.

610
00:44:59,591 --> 00:45:05,190
Speaker 0: And if you're really worried about money, you can give them a dollar range, and they'll be very good and give you restaurants that you can afford.

611
00:45:05,730 --> 00:45:06,608
Speaker 0: Don't be afraid to ask.

612
00:45:07,550 --> 00:45:11,485
Speaker 1: Yeah, and even if you ask people in the hotel, they won't just say, "Eat in the restaurant at the

613
00:45:11,525 --> 00:45:12,087
Speaker 1: hotel!"

614
00:45:12,188 --> 00:45:12,730
Speaker 1: all the time.

615
00:45:12,870 --> 00:45:13,944
Speaker 0: They'll usually say, "Don't eat

616
00:45:13,984 --> 00:45:14,166
Speaker 0: here.".

617
00:45:14,511 --> 00:45:16,109
Speaker 1: Yeah, they'll actually help you out.

618
00:45:16,930 --> 00:45:21,550
Speaker 1: And you don't want to eat at a sit-down restaurant unless it's dinner at night.

619
00:45:21,950 --> 00:45:22,713
Speaker 0: Yeah, I mean, we did that.

620
00:45:22,733 --> 00:45:24,922
Speaker 0: We dragged everyone to a Japanese sushi place.

621
00:45:24,962 --> 00:45:26,790
Speaker 0: We took the entire back room.

622
00:45:27,911 --> 00:45:30,849
Speaker 0: But it's kind of difficult to pull off, so don't worry about that so much.

623
00:45:31,630 --> 00:45:37,569
Speaker 1: If you're going to eat breakfast, because I really don't eat breakfast at a con, I'll just buy an orange juice and a bottle and drink it, and that's it.

624
00:45:38,190 --> 00:45:41,770
Speaker 1: But if you're going to eat breakfast, eat it before the con opens in the morning.

625
00:45:42,710 --> 00:45:46,230
Speaker 1: Just because, why waste precious con time when you don't have to?

626
00:45:46,670 --> 00:45:49,526
Speaker 0: Your best bet is to buy a bunch of cheapo Entenmann's donuts or something.

627
00:45:49,566 --> 00:45:50,310
Speaker 0: Just keep them in the room.

628
00:45:50,690 --> 00:45:52,009
Speaker 1: Yeah, that's another good plan.

629
00:45:52,552 --> 00:45:56,610
Speaker 0: Or our friend Nuri brought cheese Danish that was most excellent, and that kept us going at Otakon.

630
00:45:57,731 --> 00:46:11,350
Speaker 1: For lunch, you generally want to find a time in the middle of the day when there's not much happening at the con, and you want to eat somewhere food court style, or maybe even fast food, even though I never eat fast food anymore.

631
00:46:11,390 --> 00:46:13,056
Speaker 0: Yeah, well, the key is eat something.

632
00:46:13,418 --> 00:46:15,767
Speaker 0: A lot of people forget to eat at these conventions.

633
00:46:15,887 --> 00:46:16,550
Speaker 0: I'm not kidding.

634
00:46:16,811 --> 00:46:26,643
Speaker 1: Yeah, or some people are fat and they eat too much, but don't forget to eat, because you will totally be burnt out, you'll sleep too much, you'll miss con, you'll feel bad.

635
00:46:27,387 --> 00:46:27,990
Speaker 1: Remember to eat.

636
00:46:28,831 --> 00:46:30,977
Speaker 0: Yep, and corollary to that, stay hydrated.

637
00:46:31,378 --> 00:46:41,610
Speaker 0: Convention centers, especially larger ones, use cooling systems, because even though it may be winter at your con, the air in that convention center is so dry it is sucking the life out of you.

638
00:46:42,030 --> 00:46:44,142
Speaker 0: You will dehydrate twice as fast as you expect.

639
00:46:44,484 --> 00:46:45,650
Speaker 0: Drink water constantly.

640
00:46:45,811 --> 00:46:49,390
Speaker 1: I just go around drinking free water, like any time I see one, I drink like three glasses.

641
00:46:50,950 --> 00:46:56,086
Speaker 0: It's not so much a concern at small conventions, but like Otakon or Anime Expo, drink water.

642
00:46:56,106 --> 00:46:57,270
Speaker 0: I'm not even kidding.

643
00:46:58,871 --> 00:47:02,369
Speaker 1: It's pretty, especially if you're doing one of those crazy cosplays, I don't know how those people do it.

644
00:47:04,172 --> 00:47:06,309
Speaker 1: I mean, I freaking need like a camel pack in there.

645
00:47:07,930 --> 00:47:11,850
Speaker 0: That, or people are in the DDR tournaments, or people at the dances at cons.

646
00:47:13,232 --> 00:47:14,277
Speaker 0: Yeah, we'll get to the dances.

647
00:47:14,839 --> 00:47:20,650
Speaker 0: But along the lines of remembering to eat and remembering to drink, for the love of God, take a goddamn shower.

648
00:47:21,350 --> 00:47:32,950
Speaker 1: Yeah, don't, you know, if you wake up, like, I don't know, five minutes before the con opens, right, and it's something you really wanted to do, but you smell like ass, and you feel dirty, it doesn't matter, take a shower.

649
00:47:33,670 --> 00:47:36,879
Speaker 0: Yeah, I mean, this shouldn't be a problem, and it's not just anime cons.

650
00:47:37,200 --> 00:47:40,690
Speaker 0: Gaming cons are even worse, and sci-fi cons are worse still.

651
00:47:41,392 --> 00:47:46,870
Speaker 0: I don't know what it is, but these people just don't have basic hygiene, and it's not cool.

652
00:47:47,890 --> 00:47:50,450
Speaker 1: It's alright, because cons are starting to crack down on that sort of thing.

653
00:47:50,890 --> 00:47:57,270
Speaker 0: Yeah, actually, Otakon, I'm very pleased with, is bit by bit introducing policies to where if you smell bad, you've gotta leave.

654
00:47:58,350 --> 00:48:01,290
Speaker 1: Yeah, so don't be the guy who smells bad and has to leave.

655
00:48:01,791 --> 00:48:04,010
Speaker 0: If you're not sure if you smell bad, ask someone.

656
00:48:04,472 --> 00:48:09,010
Speaker 1: There are drugstores every freaking two blocks in the United States and Canada.

657
00:48:09,351 --> 00:48:13,910
Speaker 1: There is no reason that you can't go to one and get some deodorant, because your only excuse is that you left it at home.

658
00:48:15,190 --> 00:48:23,810
Speaker 0: Yeah, and the thing is, if you're gonna take part in the DDR tournament at 5 AM, or like 10 AM in the morning on Saturday, take a shower before you continue with the rest of your con experience.

659
00:48:23,970 --> 00:48:28,390
Speaker 1: And then take a shower after, or before the con, before the DDR tournament and after it.

660
00:48:28,850 --> 00:48:33,030
Speaker 0: Just take showers, because I swear to God, if I run into another smelly fanboy, I'm just gonna kill him.

661
00:48:33,431 --> 00:48:41,170
Speaker 1: Yeah, there's nothing worse than like, you're in the dealer's room, and you wanna buy something on a table, and you're trying to get close to the table to take a look at it.

662
00:48:41,570 --> 00:48:48,570
Speaker 1: And you have to squeeze in next to some guy who's like wet and slimy and nasty, and it's like, alright, now I'm not buying that.

663
00:48:49,690 --> 00:48:49,859
Speaker 1: You know?

664
00:48:52,940 --> 00:48:58,180
Speaker 0: Now one aspect that a lot of people forget about when they go with a big group to a con is communication between group members.

665
00:48:59,881 --> 00:49:11,339
Speaker 0: It's not as much of an issue as it used to be, like we used to bring radios, actually there's a- We have a story to tell, a little bit of it inside a joke.

666
00:49:14,284 --> 00:49:20,940
Speaker 0: Alright, so before cellphones were completely ubiquitous, our first convention, OhioCon.

667
00:49:21,420 --> 00:49:21,500
Speaker 0: Two.

668
00:49:22,160 --> 00:49:26,660
Speaker 0: Yeah, the second OhioCon we went to, and cellphones were pretty widespread, but- They were ubiquitous, we didn't have them.

669
00:49:26,820 --> 00:49:28,146
Speaker 0: Yeah, we didn't have cellphones.

670
00:49:28,388 --> 00:49:30,940
Speaker 0: Not, oh in fact, no one in our group had a cellphone.

671
00:49:31,522 --> 00:49:31,611
Speaker 1: Wow.

672
00:49:32,441 --> 00:49:42,000
Speaker 0: And we got there, and because we ran the RIT Anime Club, we took the walkie-talkies from the club vault and brought them with us, because, you know, we have that privilege, whatever.

673
00:49:42,860 --> 00:49:50,120
Speaker 0: So we had all these walkie-talkies, and we discovered that a lot of other people at this con had the same walkie-talkies with the same frequency bands.

674
00:49:50,300 --> 00:49:53,220
Speaker 1: Or at least other walkie-talkies on the same frequency.

675
00:49:53,921 --> 00:50:00,540
Speaker 0: And we also discovered that one channel, I forget which one it was, was the Staff/Security Coordination channel.

676
00:50:02,340 --> 00:50:11,799
Speaker 0: So, we're sitting there, and I don't know which one of us started, it was either me or Scott, but we picked it up and one of us was like into the microphone in a random channel or some other people were talking.

677
00:50:12,941 --> 00:50:13,960
Speaker 0: It's-a me, Mario!

678
00:50:15,760 --> 00:50:16,545
Speaker 1: Hello?

679
00:50:16,565 --> 00:50:18,899
Speaker 1: Is he looking at us so good?

680
00:50:20,480 --> 00:50:22,106
Speaker 0: And then we started doing Luigi.

681
00:50:22,849 --> 00:50:25,880
Speaker 0: And then other people who heard this started doing it too.

682
00:50:27,125 --> 00:50:30,840
Speaker 0: And the walkie-talkies that everyone had brought to this con became useless.

683
00:50:31,380 --> 00:50:34,900
Speaker 0: It just became a flood of Marios and Luigis yelling crap at each other.

684
00:50:35,300 --> 00:50:39,715
Speaker 0: To the point that the security people were like, "We can't use these anymore, backup plan, backup plan,".

685
00:50:39,735 --> 00:50:41,120
Speaker 0: and they stopped using the walkie-talkies.

686
00:50:42,404 --> 00:50:43,360
Speaker 0: It was hilarious.

687
00:50:44,680 --> 00:50:47,350
Speaker 1: There's nothing better than picking it up and being like, "Hello?

688
00:50:47,732 --> 00:50:48,514
Speaker 1: Is Mario there?

689
00:50:48,534 --> 00:50:49,518
Speaker 1: I cannot find

690
00:50:49,578 --> 00:50:49,739
Speaker 1: him.".

691
00:50:51,741 --> 00:50:52,184
Speaker 1: And they'd be like,

692
00:50:52,425 --> 00:50:54,378
Speaker 1: "Tiddle-A-Luigi-bo-de-ba-de-ba-do.".

693
00:50:54,981 --> 00:51:03,839
Speaker 0: But now everyone just has cell phones, make sure everyone has each other's numbers, and make sure that if- Don't expect that anyone's going to answer your phone.

694
00:51:04,640 --> 00:51:08,220
Speaker 0: Because if you call someone, odds are they don't notice it ringing until an hour later.

695
00:51:09,262 --> 00:51:10,980
Speaker 0: So never expect quick communication.

696
00:51:12,301 --> 00:51:14,899
Speaker 1: And then you have those next telephones that do the walkie-talkie thing.

697
00:51:15,480 --> 00:51:23,840
Speaker 1: Even then, someone won't feel it vibrating, they'll be busy and they can't pick it up, they'll be watching a movie, they won't want to pick it up, they won't hear it ring.

698
00:51:23,980 --> 00:51:25,640
Speaker 1: Just don't worry about it.

699
00:51:25,880 --> 00:51:27,826
Speaker 0: If you're the caller, call someone once.

700
00:51:28,307 --> 00:51:32,640
Speaker 0: If they don't answer, call someone else, or don't worry about it, you're not going to get ahold of them.

701
00:51:32,740 --> 00:51:38,360
Speaker 1: Yeah, most of the time when you're calling, you're looking for people to group up, or you're trying to figure out where people are.

702
00:51:39,140 --> 00:51:44,080
Speaker 1: Maybe in the future we'll have awesome GPS technology, you'll know exactly where everyone is, just looking at a little screen.

703
00:51:45,000 --> 00:51:48,212
Speaker 0: And if you're calling people to organize dinner, it's already too late.

704
00:51:48,272 --> 00:51:50,540
Speaker 0: You had to coordinate the dinner long before it's done.

705
00:51:50,680 --> 00:51:54,291
Speaker 1: If it's a sitting down dinner, you have to take care of that way earlier.

706
00:51:54,331 --> 00:51:57,280
Speaker 1: You have to say early in the morning when everyone's still in the hotel room.

707
00:51:57,380 --> 00:51:59,129
Speaker 1: "Alright everyone, remember...".

708
00:51:59,330 --> 00:52:01,300
Speaker 1: And this will be the third time you're reminding them, by the way.

709
00:52:02,040 --> 00:52:06,133
Speaker 1: "Tonight, at 8, we're all going to meet here and then decide on a restaurant.

710
00:52:06,394 --> 00:52:07,718
Speaker 1: If you're not there at 8, you're not

711
00:52:07,778 --> 00:52:08,039
Speaker 1: going.".

712
00:52:08,420 --> 00:52:21,020
Speaker 0: Now if you're the one receiving calls, especially us, or if you're the person who's running this room or you're the one coordinating everything, just look at your phone periodically and see all the missed messages and then call back the people who deserve calls back.

713
00:52:22,080 --> 00:52:27,360
Speaker 1: Yeah, I make it a note that whenever I enter or leave an event at the con, I always just look at the phone.

714
00:52:28,041 --> 00:52:30,960
Speaker 1: Mostly to see what time it is, but also to see if anyone left me a voicemail.

715
00:52:31,360 --> 00:52:31,500
Speaker 0: Yep.

716
00:52:32,683 --> 00:52:34,809
Speaker 0: And make sure you have some predefined meeting places.

717
00:52:34,869 --> 00:52:39,300
Speaker 0: Like, pick a few places where you can meet that are obvious and you'll be able to find each other.

718
00:52:39,821 --> 00:52:43,040
Speaker 0: Again, not so much a concern at small cons, but large cons, it's critical.

719
00:52:44,044 --> 00:52:44,599
Speaker 1: Very critical.

720
00:52:45,403 --> 00:52:48,160
Speaker 0: And make sure it's a place where you can actually find the person.

721
00:52:48,280 --> 00:52:53,980
Speaker 1: Make sure it's a place everyone actually knows, because a lot of times you'll be like, "Alright, everyone meet here," and people will go right, and they'll all go someplace different.

722
00:52:54,320 --> 00:52:54,899
Speaker 1: Because they're all dumb.

723
00:52:55,220 --> 00:53:00,340
Speaker 0: Or they'll all meet somewhere, and the place you specified is a giant auditorium with a movie playing full of people.

724
00:53:00,962 --> 00:53:01,051
Speaker 1: Yeah.

725
00:53:01,360 --> 00:53:01,468
Speaker 1: Great.

726
00:53:01,880 --> 00:53:04,991
Speaker 1: You usually want to pick an outdoors location that's not crowded.

727
00:53:05,212 --> 00:53:07,600
Speaker 1: That is sort of like a little ways from the con.

728
00:53:07,921 --> 00:53:13,260
Speaker 0: And if you go to Otacon, don't pick the freaking fountains, because everyone's trying to meet everyone at the fountains.

729
00:53:14,381 --> 00:53:14,899
Speaker 1: Fountains bad.

730
00:53:15,260 --> 00:53:15,462
Speaker 1: Yeah.

731
00:53:15,764 --> 00:53:17,600
Speaker 0: Plus all the cosplayers are there constantly.

732
00:53:18,860 --> 00:53:22,940
Speaker 1: We usually pick, like, sculptures, or any sort of landmark is always good.

733
00:53:24,300 --> 00:53:30,900
Speaker 0: Now, almost all cons have a dealer's room, and this will be pivotal to your experience at a con if you've never been to a con before.

734
00:53:31,762 --> 00:53:38,180
Speaker 0: I mean, just to give you an example, Otacon, the dealer's room is, what, eleven football fields?

735
00:53:38,282 --> 00:53:39,120
Speaker 1: It's not eleven football fields.

736
00:53:39,140 --> 00:53:40,360
Speaker 0: It was nine football fields, right?

737
00:53:40,500 --> 00:53:41,580
Speaker 1: I thought it was like four or five.

738
00:53:41,720 --> 00:53:42,899
Speaker 0: No, it was nine at least.

739
00:53:43,380 --> 00:53:43,616
Speaker 1: It was huge.

740
00:53:43,680 --> 00:53:44,306
Speaker 1: It doesn't matter.

741
00:53:44,347 --> 00:53:45,680
Speaker 1: It's very, very large.

742
00:53:46,420 --> 00:53:48,260
Speaker 1: You can't see from one end to the other.

743
00:53:49,120 --> 00:53:55,560
Speaker 1: I mean, it was about as big as more than one whole room at the Jacob Javits Center.

744
00:53:56,443 --> 00:53:56,958
Speaker 1: Very large.

745
00:53:57,582 --> 00:54:03,120
Speaker 0: Now, basically to sum up, make sure you have money to pay for gas and everything home.

746
00:54:03,540 --> 00:54:05,320
Speaker 0: Don't spend all your money in the dealer's room.

747
00:54:06,200 --> 00:54:14,400
Speaker 0: Two, you probably want to pay with credit cards, because all the dealers will take it, even at little crap cons, and you don't want to be carrying wads of cash around in a sea of people.

748
00:54:14,560 --> 00:54:23,380
Speaker 1: Yeah, but sometimes, like, one time I tried to buy a Gundam with a credit card, and they accepted it, but I had to go to, like, another booth and pay there, and it was a pain in the ass.

749
00:54:23,460 --> 00:54:24,643
Speaker 1: So have cash also.

750
00:54:25,184 --> 00:54:32,580
Speaker 1: But to make sure you can make it home, have enough cash to make it home and leave it in your hotel room in a safe spot so you can't possibly spend it.

751
00:54:32,880 --> 00:54:36,670
Speaker 0: Furthermore, and this is kind of an aside, but ATMs and cash.

752
00:54:37,171 --> 00:54:40,480
Speaker 0: Bring cash with you to the con and keep it in the room or something.

753
00:54:40,981 --> 00:54:44,119
Speaker 0: Or, if you don't have it with you yet, get it immediately from an ATM.

754
00:54:44,600 --> 00:54:49,860
Speaker 1: And make as few withdrawals from ATMs as possible, because near convention centers, the ATM fees are insane.

755
00:54:50,040 --> 00:54:51,420
Speaker 0: Well, not only that, more importantly...

756
00:54:51,440 --> 00:54:52,939
Speaker 1: You don't pay ATM fees, but other people do.

757
00:54:53,740 --> 00:54:54,388
Speaker 0: Uh, yeah, whatever.

758
00:54:54,428 --> 00:54:55,340
Speaker 0: Your bank kinda sucks.

759
00:54:55,680 --> 00:54:56,199
Speaker 1: My bank's awesome.

760
00:54:57,501 --> 00:55:05,080
Speaker 0: Paying...using ATMs is important more because the ATMs within a several mile radius of any large con will be completely empty by Friday night.

761
00:55:05,522 --> 00:55:07,300
Speaker 1: And no one fills those things on the weekends.

762
00:55:07,940 --> 00:55:13,056
Speaker 0: I was actually at a con, uh, Anime Central, where it was time to pay the lady for the suite.

763
00:55:13,357 --> 00:55:14,380
Speaker 0: So I owed her, like, 80 bucks.

764
00:55:14,882 --> 00:55:18,440
Speaker 0: And I figure, alright, fine, I go down to the ATM and I try to get money out, and it's empty.

765
00:55:19,301 --> 00:55:21,380
Speaker 0: And now I have no way of paying this woman.

766
00:55:23,066 --> 00:55:23,340
Speaker 1: Sucks.

767
00:55:23,800 --> 00:55:26,860
Speaker 0: Yeah, I ended up writing her a check, which I felt bad about.

768
00:55:27,320 --> 00:55:29,619
Speaker 1: Yeah, I don't write checks so much.

769
00:55:30,300 --> 00:55:30,558
Speaker 0: Yeah.

770
00:55:32,042 --> 00:55:34,500
Speaker 1: Another thing is, you generally want to have a dealer's room strategy.

771
00:55:35,140 --> 00:55:38,960
Speaker 1: Like, if it's a little tiny dealer's room at a tiny con, don't worry about it.

772
00:55:39,000 --> 00:55:42,660
Speaker 1: Just go in there once or twice and look over everything and buy anything you really want.

773
00:55:43,481 --> 00:55:52,600
Speaker 1: And on Sunday, you can probably...well, on the last day of any convention, any dealer is usually trying to sell, you know, a whole bunch of stuff at the last minute.

774
00:55:52,860 --> 00:55:53,780
Speaker 0: You'll get crazy deals.

775
00:55:54,000 --> 00:55:56,060
Speaker 1: You can probably get a crazy deal if you're savvy.

776
00:55:56,380 --> 00:55:59,199
Speaker 0: Our friend Scott Johnson is probably the Mac Master of this.

777
00:55:59,620 --> 00:55:59,711
Speaker 1: Yeah.

778
00:55:59,880 --> 00:56:07,200
Speaker 0: We don't know how he does it, but Sunday, he just went into the dealer's room on his own, and he walked out with, like, a sack full of various goodies.

779
00:56:07,804 --> 00:56:09,180
Speaker 0: And it cost him almost nothing.

780
00:56:09,341 --> 00:56:12,578
Speaker 1: Yeah, he comes up to us and he's like, "Here's all the DVDs I got at the

781
00:56:12,598 --> 00:56:12,880
Speaker 1: con.".

782
00:56:12,940 --> 00:56:14,145
Speaker 1: And he's got this, like, tower.

783
00:56:14,165 --> 00:56:18,080
Speaker 1: It's like a five foot tall...well, not like five feet, but like a two and a half foot tall tower of DVDs.

784
00:56:18,240 --> 00:56:20,886
Speaker 1: And he's like, "Yep, I got 40 DVDs here.

785
00:56:21,287 --> 00:56:23,973
Speaker 1: Cost me, uh, let's see, 40 DVDs.

786
00:56:24,013 --> 00:56:25,577
Speaker 1: It usually costs, let's see, times

787
00:56:25,577 --> 00:56:27,463
Speaker 1: $2,800.".

788
00:56:27,463 --> 00:56:28,993
Speaker 1: He's like, "Yep, I paid, like, 150 bucks for

789
00:56:29,013 --> 00:56:29,113
Speaker 1: this.".

790
00:56:30,462 --> 00:56:31,449
Speaker 1: And you're like, "Holy

791
00:56:31,469 --> 00:56:32,778
Speaker 1: damn.".

792
00:56:33,221 --> 00:56:35,699
Speaker 0: Granted, he's got a lot of bad anime as a result of this.

793
00:56:36,162 --> 00:56:37,140
Speaker 1: Yeah, but, you know...

794
00:56:37,140 --> 00:56:38,208
Speaker 0: But also the goodies.

795
00:56:38,289 --> 00:56:39,820
Speaker 0: He gets every little goodie for nothing.

796
00:56:41,043 --> 00:56:41,103
Speaker 1: Mhm.

797
00:56:41,123 --> 00:56:42,570
Speaker 1: Also, there's a lot of free stuff.

798
00:56:42,590 --> 00:56:44,540
Speaker 1: they give away in dealer's rooms often.

799
00:56:44,740 --> 00:56:46,189
Speaker 0: Well, only really at large cons.

800
00:56:46,229 --> 00:56:48,100
Speaker 0: I mean, I didn't get crap at Katsu-Con.

801
00:56:48,280 --> 00:56:48,701
Speaker 1: Oh, yeah.

802
00:56:49,001 --> 00:57:02,860
Speaker 1: But when they give away free stuff, you want to have a time when you're about to go to your hotel room, go in, collect every free thing that you want at all, and then bring it back to your hotel room, because carrying it around the con sucks.

803
00:57:03,302 --> 00:57:04,508
Speaker 0: That goes for buying things, too.

804
00:57:04,548 --> 00:57:06,940
Speaker 0: If you're buying anything big, buy it before you go into the room.

805
00:57:08,100 --> 00:57:13,760
Speaker 0: Now, also, don't buy things that you can get outside of the con, because you'll probably pay a lot more.

806
00:57:14,060 --> 00:57:14,842
Speaker 1: Yeah, be smart.

807
00:57:15,143 --> 00:57:21,420
Speaker 1: If you see something in the convention center that you can buy online or you can buy in another store, there's no reason to buy it there.

808
00:57:21,760 --> 00:57:23,464
Speaker 0: The worst thing are those frickin' swords.

809
00:57:23,864 --> 00:57:31,240
Speaker 0: Every con now, they'll have one or two guys selling, like, paintball guns and airsoft guns and giant swords and stupid crap like that.

810
00:57:31,841 --> 00:57:33,587
Speaker 0: And fanboys just eat it up and they buy 'em.

811
00:57:33,607 --> 00:57:34,610
Speaker 0: I don't know why.

812
00:57:34,630 --> 00:57:38,040
Speaker 0: They're overpriced, they're crappy, you can't actually carry it around at the con.

813
00:57:39,600 --> 00:57:44,758
Speaker 1: Now, if you're over 18 and a little kid comes up to you and says, "Hey, if I give you money, will you buy me a

814
00:57:44,798 --> 00:57:45,099
Speaker 1: sword?".

815
00:57:45,701 --> 00:57:46,242
Speaker 1: You say, "All

816
00:57:46,282 --> 00:57:46,463
Speaker 1: right.".

817
00:57:46,844 --> 00:57:49,250
Speaker 1: You don't say no, even though that's a good thing to say.

818
00:57:49,370 --> 00:57:51,395
Speaker 1: You sure as hell don't just say yes, sure.

819
00:57:51,756 --> 00:57:53,140
Speaker 1: That's also a stupid thing to say.

820
00:57:53,581 --> 00:57:55,345
Speaker 1: What you say is, "How much is the

821
00:57:55,405 --> 00:57:55,766
Speaker 1: sword?".

822
00:57:56,388 --> 00:57:57,971
Speaker 1: And let's say he says the sword's 100 bucks.

823
00:57:57,992 --> 00:58:00,297
Speaker 1: You say, "You give me 150 and I'll buy you the $100

824
00:58:00,297 --> 00:58:00,397
Speaker 1: sword.".

825
00:58:01,641 --> 00:58:05,560
Speaker 1: That's the way to do it, because then you go and you get a $50 awesome thing somewhere else.

826
00:58:06,441 --> 00:58:08,700
Speaker 0: Yeah, see, I generally disagree with that.

827
00:58:08,980 --> 00:58:09,651
Speaker 1: No, I like it.

828
00:58:09,692 --> 00:58:10,139
Speaker 1: It's a good way.

829
00:58:10,420 --> 00:58:21,540
Speaker 0: Well, one, that doesn't work, because usually they ship the sword to your hotel room or they give it to you in a giant sealed box and you're escorted out, then you have to take it and store it somewhere.

830
00:58:22,260 --> 00:58:23,659
Speaker 0: Mostly they make you ship them home.

831
00:58:24,860 --> 00:58:25,487
Speaker 1: I'd ship them home.

832
00:58:25,608 --> 00:58:26,720
Speaker 1: I'd just give them the kid's address.

833
00:58:28,060 --> 00:58:29,659
Speaker 0: Yeah, that doesn't work if you have the credit card.

834
00:58:30,925 --> 00:58:31,320
Speaker 1: I guess not.

835
00:58:31,320 --> 00:58:32,639
Speaker 0: Because the billing address doesn't match up.

836
00:58:33,342 --> 00:58:33,880
Speaker 1: It all depends.

837
00:58:34,000 --> 00:58:34,727
Speaker 0: Yeah, Scott's dumb.

838
00:58:34,767 --> 00:58:36,079
Speaker 0: Don't buy swords for little kids.

839
00:58:36,580 --> 00:58:38,313
Speaker 1: Well, not like little kids, but like a 16-year-old kid.

840
00:58:39,280 --> 00:58:40,788
Speaker 0: Yeah, a 16-year-old punk kid.

841
00:58:40,849 --> 00:58:42,860
Speaker 0: You want to give him a sword at an anime con.

842
00:58:43,420 --> 00:58:45,640
Speaker 1: Hey, if he's done with it, that's his problem.

843
00:58:47,542 --> 00:58:48,907
Speaker 1: Plus, you can always deny.

844
00:58:48,927 --> 00:58:52,700
Speaker 1: You can be like, "No, I was just buying the sword for me," and then you make off with the kid's money.

845
00:58:53,870 --> 00:58:54,119
Speaker 1: All right.

846
00:58:54,180 --> 00:58:55,018
Speaker 1: He was dumb enough to give it to you.

847
00:58:55,680 --> 00:59:03,640
Speaker 0: Well, that said, we've talked a long time about a lot of topics with very little organization, and I think we're going to have to do a part three in this series.

848
00:59:03,960 --> 00:59:05,000
